1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,500
Employee onboarding should create confidence.

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:12,600
But for growing teams, the first days are often
scattered across messages and spreadsheets.

3
00:00:12,600 --> 00:00:16,600
And disconnected documents. That is why
we built Simple Board:

4
00:00:16,600 --> 00:00:20,829
a native macOS onboarding workspace
for small team owners and their employees.

5
00:00:21,461 --> 00:00:25,500
Here is the Sunrise Bistro demo.
From one dashboard, an owner can see

6
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,960
active employees, published programs, completion,
and people who may need support.

7
00:00:31,585 --> 00:00:35,400
The manager opens Kitchen Staff Onboarding.
Programs are organized into stages

8
00:00:35,400 --> 00:00:40,000
with deadlines, clear outcomes,
and seven learning formats:

9
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
video, reading, checklist, quiz,
task, document, and meeting.

10
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,548
Preview mode lets the manager experience the journey
safely without changing any employee record.

11
00:00:51,162 --> 00:00:55,200
On the employee record, the owner can see
the assigned program, stage progress,

12
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:59,000
and completion evidence. Now we switch
to the employee point of view.

13
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Budi signs in with his own account
and immediately sees one focused journey,

14
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,926
his progress, and the next action to complete.

15
00:01:07,356 --> 00:01:11,300
Budi acknowledges the Kitchen Code of Conduct.
His progress moves from seventy-one

16
00:01:11,300 --> 00:01:16,000
to eighty-six percent. When the owner returns,
the dashboard already shows the updated result.

17
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,700
The Performance view turns that activity
into a clear signal:

18
00:01:20,700 --> 00:01:25,006
who is on track, who has completed onboarding,
and who needs help.

19
00:01:25,624 --> 00:01:29,500
We built Simple Board in Codex.
We started from a browser prototype

20
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:34,000
and asked Codex to help turn it
into a real native SwiftUI application.

21
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Codex worked directly inside the repository:
creating the Xcode project, typed data models,

22
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:44,500
an observable application store, local persistence,
Keychain credentials, responsive macOS layouts,

23
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:50,231
previews, the employee portal,
and automated tests.

24
00:01:50,844 --> 00:01:56,500
Our workflow was iterative. Codex inspected screenshots,
reproduced layout defects, and changed the SwiftUI code.

25
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:02,600
It ran Xcode builds and tests, then used the evidence
to refine the next pass.

26
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:08,193
That let one small team move from idea to a working,
TestFlight-ready Mac app much faster.

27
00:02:08,841 --> 00:02:13,400
GPT-5.6 was the reasoning layer
throughout that process.

28
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:18,300
It translated product goals into a safe owner
and employee permission model,

29
00:02:18,300 --> 00:02:23,200
designed local-first storage and secure invitations,
and traced difficult layout and state bugs.

30
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:28,200
It also planned end-to-end test coverage.
We used it as an engineering partner:

31
00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:33,556
describe the intent, reason over the code,
verify the result, and iterate.

32
00:02:33,980 --> 00:02:37,800
Simple Board makes onboarding clear for leaders
and actionable for employees.

33
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:41,400
Because every first day should feel
like the company was ready for you.
